        "number": 2,
        "title": "Guarding the dedicated — treasury stewardship and the provenance of consecrated wealth",
        "range": "26:20-28",
        "excerpt": "This Shelomoth and his relatives had charge of all the treasures of the dedicated gifts which King David and the heads of the fathers' households … had dedicated. (26:26)",
        "body": "The chapter's second unit shifts from security to stewardship. Verses 20-28 organize Levitical oversight of two distinct categories of Temple wealth: the ongoing treasury of the house of God (v.20) and the treasury of dedicated gifts (vv. 20, 26-28). The distinction is theologically important. The first is the Temple's operating reserve — the regular income from tithes, offerings, and temple-tax. The second is a special repository of gifts that have been formally consecrated to God, often from military campaigns.\n\nThe lineage assigned to the treasury of dedicated gifts is itself significant. Shebuel, 'the son of Gershom, the son of Moses,' holds the office of nagid — officer, designated leader — over the treasuries (v.24). The Mosaic pedigree is deliberate. The man responsible for the most sensitive financial stewardship in Israel descends directly from the nation's founder. The Chronicler honors that lineage not as aristocratic entitlement but as a statement about the continuity of covenantal responsibility: the house of Moses that received the Torah at Sinai now receives the consecrated wealth of Israel's wars.\n\nVerses 26-28 list the donors to the dedicated treasury: King David, military commanders, Samuel, Saul, Abner, and Joab. The theological breadth of this list is striking. Samuel is the last judge and the one who anointed David; Saul is the rejected king; Abner is Saul's general who shifted allegiance to David only late and died in political intrigue; Joab is David's capable but morally compromised general. All of them dedicated gifts that the same treasury now holds. The Chronicler is not issuing retrospective moral grades on these men; he is insisting that the act of formal consecration (*qadash*) transfers ownership permanently to God regardless of the donor's biography. What is dedicated is dedicated. The treasury preserves an unbroken chain of consecration from Israel's entire monarchical story, including its shadows.\n\nThe specific note that spoils were dedicated 'to repair the house of the LORD' (v.27) echoes a theme the Chronicler will develop in 2 Chronicles (especially 2 Chronicles 24:4-14; 34:8-13): the Temple requires periodic maintenance, and its maintenance is funded by the willing consecration of material gain. Warfare and worship are not opposed spheres; the fruit of God-given military victory properly returns to strengthen God's house.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Qadash* (dedicated/consecrate, vv. 26-28) — the Piel form meaning to treat as holy, to formally set apart. *Nagid* (officer, v.24) — one set forward as leader; used of Saul's anointing (1 Samuel 10:1), of Solomon (1 Chronicles 29:22), and here of the treasury overseer, a prestigious title applied to a financial steward."
